Repeat this exercise when considering third and fourth principal component, and then tenth and eleventh. What do you notice? Justify your answer from theoretical perspective behind PCA.

PCA is a procedure that convert each instance of the dataset into its principal components: the first principal component has the largest possible variance, while the succeeding ones in turn has the highest variance possible under the constraint that it is orthogonal to the preceding components. Variance, informally, measures how far a set of values are spread out from their average value. So it, in short words, works as "summary" of the data designed to preserve the maximum informations possible with the dimensionality reduction choosen.

The graphs behind are a good representations of the concepts here described: the more the selected components get closer to the principal ones, the wider data-points split on the graph, and its depends on the maximized variance obtained thanks to PCAnalysis. It can be noticed looking at the axis values of the graphs, that grows up from the left to the right in the image behind.

Why it is so important? Well, despite the image representations do not represent excellently this usefull compression, PCA perform the best information compression for machine learning classifiers, that need to work on well-discriminated datas to obtain the best results possible.

5. How would you decide on the number of principal components needed to preserve data without much distortion?

There are two significant approaches to perform decision on the number of PC needed to "preserve" data: the most empirical regards the image visualization and follow the reasoning according to the choise has to be made based on the result, or rather the decision depends on how "good" is the visualization of reconstructed images, without considering the mathematical aspect of the problem.

The most significant approach is to choose a reasonable value for cumulative variance and taking the principal components consequently; e.g. taking the first k eigenvectors that capture at least 85% of the total variance.

In the graph below it is illustrated the ratio between the cumulative variance and the number of principal components, and immediately after is showed the choosen number of principal components following an heuristic like the one described above.

explained_variance = np.var(X_T, axis=0)
explained_variance_ratio = explained_variance / np.sum(explained_variance)
cum=np.cumsum(explained_variance_ratio)
plt.plot(cum,'--o')
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()
desired=np.argmax(cum>0.9)
print("Good Number of PC=",desired,"with Cumulative Variance =",cum[desired])

Good Number of PC= 27 with Cumulative Variance = 0.900120683559679

2. Naive Bayes Classifier¶

In this stage, we will see how dimensionality reduction using PCA works when applied together with a machine learning classifier. We will use the Naive Bayes Classifier both on original dataset and dataset projected on two components extracted through PCA method.

Formulation:¶

$$\tilde{y} = \underset{y \in 1,2,3,4}{argmax} \ P(y | x_1, x_2,.., x_d) = \underset{y \in 1,2,3,4}{argmax} \ P(y) \prod_{i=1}^{d} P(x_i | y) = \underset{y \in 1,2,3,4}{argmax} \ \frac{1}{4}\prod_{i=1}^{d}\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi\sigma_y^2}} e^{-\frac{(x_i - \mu_y)^2}{ 2\sigma_y^2}} $$

4. Repeat the splitting, training, and testing for the data projected onto rst two principal components, then third and fourth principal components. Compare results: what are your conclusions?

The stats printed behind briefly summarize the importance of the usage of PCA for dimension reduction: Principal components analysis allow us to reduct intensely the dimension of our dataset, with a minimum loss of information. In the example behind, we can see how PCA works in terms of:

-dimensionality lowering: using two Principal Components to "resume" the dataset allows to reduct dimensions of a 10^-3 factor

-information loss: the accuracy of NB Classifier on prediction can easily represent a good example of the quality of PCA compression method. Our classifier, with the usage of the only first two principal components, can perform a good classification accuracy, which value generally stands between the 70% and 90% compared to the NB classifier accuracy using uncompressed images.

It means that, despite a huge compression of data using PCA, the classification algorithms could works with excellente results.

Lastly, using 3rd and 4th PC we have a normal decreasing of the performance of the classifier due to the fact that these ones are not the best principal components and the dataset representation on these two do not perform the best cumulative variance of the whole dataset. So, in short words, it is more difficult "to distinguish" between one datapoint to the others when the dataset is projected among these two components (and the graph in the first exercise is a clear example). Furthermore, the classifier is, most of the times, meaningless becouse the accuracy is worse then a simple "coin flipping" (<0.5 accuracy)
